    <h1>Tops / Flops</h1><div id="preamble">
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p><strong>Start » Statistics → Type of statistic: Item / Tops / Flops</strong></p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_tops_flops">1. Tops / Flops</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This statistic shows the revenue data sorted according to <em><strong>tops</strong></em> (those are the items that were sold most often during the selected <em><strong>time span</strong></em>) and <em><strong>flops</strong></em> (those are the items that were sold least often during this time span). Default setting for the time span: <strong>the current week</strong>.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock warning">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-warning" title="Warning"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Time span for the analysis</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you choose the setting <strong>Date selection</strong> as the <strong>Time span</strong>, then please note that data will not be included in the analysis if it is more than <em><strong>6 months old</strong></em>. This is also true for the <em><strong>data export</strong></em> (section 4).</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_details_about_the_statistic">2. Details about the statistic</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Depending on which option you select, either the <em><strong>Tops - most frequently sold items</strong></em> or the <em><strong>Flops - least frequently sold items</strong></em> will be displayed for the selected time span. The items will be listed in descending order. In other words, the list of tops will begin with the item that was sold the most often. This list will end with whichever top item was sold the least often. The list of flops is exactly the opposite. In other words, the list begins with whichever item was sold the least often and progresses with items that were sold more and more often. In this statistic you can see, e.g. which items are lucrative and which are not. For example, you may notice that the warehouse and operating costs of an item are higher than the profit.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Data for item bundles</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This statistic takes sold quantities into consideration when calculating basic items from item bundles. However, it does not take the purchase price and revenue into consideration.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In image 1, you can see <em><strong>tops</strong></em> listed in descending order.</p>
</div>
